text: 9/ I am simply asking for folks to understand what I am building, why I am building this way. If you have constructive criticism, I am happy to receive it. But I can't tell the difference when you troll me. I can't tell if you support or hate the project.

8/ As much as I pride myself in being cool, collected, and in control, I really lost it here and became so discouraged and upset. I apologize that this slipped and engagement went heavily into the troll realm. I recognize this mistake and will move forward.

7/ I know that you are lighthearted in how you approach and troll me. Tonight, I am exhausted - from over three straight weeks of work on this project - and I let my emotions slip and I engaged with the trolls making fun of the work I do. I don't see sarcasm well in text.
6/ Brands, especially large brands, have entire teams dedicated to researching infringement and completing takedowns. At this time, it's only me.
5/ I'm simply asking folks to be respectful of what I'm trying to build. I'm also learning how to work through all of this as a new brand, and it's tough to manage - a big learning curve.

4/ It's important for me to protect the IP and trademark because if I don't take it seriously, and let things go, when something serious does happen - the court will not protect me. Period. This is how it works.

3/ I understand the web3 space is filled with derivatives, projects offering IP and cc0 open source. I get it. I love those projects myself. However, offering IP and cc0 is not possible for Tigerbob if I'm going to expand into web2 spaces to create merchandise and otherwise.

2/ I do this quietly and have been doing so for the past few months. Legal is expensive, starting a brand is expensive. When you take steps into copyright and gaining control over something you can build with, you need a foundation of IP that protects that.

Hi all. @grelysian here. I just want to take note that while web3 has lots fun of trolling and memeing, I am also doing my best to build this brand and protect the mark. When I see my work reposted and remixed, I have to take steps to get things taken down.

The type of funding that would be needed is for continued legal expenses, the construction, manufacturing, and iteration of custom merchandise (where you interface directly with manufacturers - not like Printful or other on-demand services). These things cost money in USD.

Because of market conditions, it will not be fully possible to realize a true funding from the mint. Secondary is not reliable, although I do understand we will make some money it is not something we will know until it occurs, and therefore this was not factored in.

For those folks who think the discussion is now about money instead of art, I implore you to read https://t.co/SJJ99gdJbO and https://t.co/2dBfem5JD7 it has been 100% clear that this project is a genesis funding for the Tigerbob brand.

8/12 Our team then manually reduced this list from 56k to about 25k using additional research based on our â€œred flagsâ€ The data we reviewed was pulled directly from your premint entry. We reviewed patterns in this data set, and determined what would become our â€œred flags.â€
7/12 We partnered with @flipsidecrypto and @mulligan for a bulk of the review. Using on-chain data Flipside helped us narrow down our entries from 111k to about 56k.
6/12 Our team utilized similar methods to de-bot (remove invalid entries from bad actors trying to game the system) our PREMINT raffle as the @moonbirds team. We worked on this from May 1 - May 14.
